 Detection of SARM-1 protein in human brain and rat brain and spinal cord tissue
Anterograde axon degeneration, which appears to involve caspase-3, is reported during neuronal death induced by trauma and disease. The SARM1 (sterile alpha and HEAT (hsp70/hsc70) repeat-motif containing protein 1) gene was previously thought to be expressed only in non-neuronal cells. Recently, however, several groups independently reported that SARM1 mRNA is also expressed in the brain. We sought to verify this report using a SARM1 antibody raised against our expression construct of the human protein. We detected SARM1 in multiple human brain regions and cell types. We also detected SARM1 in rat spinal cord and brains. Thus SARM1 appears to be a novel component of axon and neuron degeneration pathways in both the nervous system and peripheral tissues. .
